  "prompt": "Who invented the concept of money?",
  "response": "The concept of money did not have a single inventor; rather, it developed independently in different cultures over time as a solution to the limitations of barter systems. The earliest forms of money likely included commodity money, where items such as shells, grains, or livestock were used as mediums of exchange based on their intrinsic value.\n\nOne of the earliest recorded uses of money dates back to Mesopotamia around 3000 BCE, where the Sumerians used barley as a commodity for trade. The Chinese are also credited with early forms of money, including the use of cowry shells and later metal objects. By around 600 BCE, the Lydians (in modern-day Turkey) are often credited with creating the first standardized coins, which facilitated trade by providing a consistent unit of value.\n\nOverall, the evolution of money is a complex process that reflects the economic, social, and technological developments of various civilizations throughout history.",
